<title>Paper Scout Research Report — 2026-06-15</title>

<p><b>Opening.</b> This run kept circling one question: if scalable robot learning needs far more data than any lab can teleoperate, where should the supervision come from? Two fresh papers give strikingly different answers. <b>μ₀</b> argues that unlabeled internet-style videos are enough if the world model predicts the right intermediate representation — 3D interaction traces. <b>Hy-Embodied-0.5-VLA</b> argues the opposite: build custom hardware, collect 10,000 hours of sub-millimeter action-labeled demonstrations, and refine with offline RL. Both report strong real-robot numbers; both also arrive with material code-release caveats. Alongside them, the pool offered several sharp agent-training papers — on procedural credit assignment, harness evolution, view-consistent GUI grounding, and interleaved generation — that are worth watching even if they did not get a full deep dive this time.</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> μ₀ (arXiv 2606.13769) is the clearest research seed. It reframes world-model pretraining around a compact, inspectable, embodiment-agnostic motion representation, and it backs the claim with both trace-forecasting metrics and real-robot transfer.</p>
</callout>

<h1>Theme 1 — World Models from Unlabeled Video</h1>

<p>The dominant recipe for robot foundation models today is pretraining on large action-labeled corpora (π₀, π₀.5, OpenVLA, etc.). A dissenting view says video itself should be enough, provided the model predicts a representation that discards irrelevant appearance and keeps actionable geometry. Two recent papers sit on this branch.</p>

