<h2>μ₀: A Scalable 3D Interaction-Trace World Model</h2>

<p>Lee et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.13769">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.13769">PDF</a> · <a href="https://mu0-wm.github.io/">Project</a></p>

<p>μ₀ occupies a deliberately chosen middle ground between pixel generators and action-predicting VLAs. Pixel models spend most of their capacity on appearance; VLA models need embodiment-specific action labels that do not transfer. The authors instead ask the model to forecast <b>3D interaction traces</b> — future trajectories of semantic keypoints on objects, tools, hands, and contact regions. The same trace forecast can be consumed by different downstream action experts for different robots.</p>

<p><b>TraceExtract.</b> Because no large trace dataset existed, the authors built an offline engine that converts heterogeneous human and robot videos into supervised trace tuples. It selects entity-centric keypoints via DINOv2 clustering, lifts and tracks them in a globally aligned 3D frame using VGGT and TAPIP3D, and segments motion into short events via acceleration peaks and valleys. A VLM then captions each event from start/mid/end frames. The result is roughly 8× the scale of prior 3D-trace datasets.</p>

<p><b>Model.</b> μ₀ uses a frozen SmolVLM2-2.2B prefix for semantic conditioning and adds a 20-layer permutation-equivariant “Trace Expert.” Each query keypoint is represented as a history token plus a set of noisy B-spline control points. The expert is trained with conditional flow matching on those control points, plus a validity head for occlusion and a rigidity loss that keeps keypoints within the same DINO cluster from stretching unnaturally.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:mu0:overview]]</p>

<p>After pretraining, the entire μ₀ model is frozen. A small action expert is trained on robot demonstrations that consumes intermediate trace-denoising features as motion tokens, fuses them into VLM features through a gated cross-attention layer, and predicts action chunks via flow matching. The action expert is the only place embodiment-specific labels appear.</p>

<p><b>Why B-splines matter.</b> The paper replaces a dense H=32-step future trace with D=10 cubic B-spline control points — roughly a 3× compression in the target dimension — while keeping the curve smooth. I reconstructed this target from Appendix B.2 to see whether the compression is lossy in practice. On a noisy synthetic 3D spiral, the ridge-least-squares fit recovers the trace with MSE ≈ 0.0028 and only 30 scalars instead of 96.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:mu0:bspline]]</p>

