<h2>Hy-Embodied-0.5-VLA: A Real-World Robot Learning Stack</h2>

<p>Tencent Robotics X × Tencent Hy Team (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.14409">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.14409">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/Tencent-Hunyuan/Hy-Embodied-0.5-VLA">GitHub</a></p>

<p>HyVLA-0.5 is presented not as a model but as a stack: custom fingertip UMI grippers in an optical motion-capture cage, a 4B Mixture-of-Transformers VLM pretrained on embodied corpora, a 370M-parameter flow-matching action expert, a parameter-free compact memory encoder, offline preference-optimization RL, and an asynchronous high-frequency deployment pipeline. The paper reports 90.9% / 90.1% on RoboTwin 2.0 Clean / Randomized and near-ceiling success on four real-robot X-Trainer tasks after FlowPRO post-training.</p>

<p><b>Data.</b> The custom rig records 10,000+ hours of egocentric human demonstrations. Optical mocap replaces the visual SLAM used in standard UMI, giving sub-millimeter 6-DoF gripper poses in a single world frame. The same trajectories are reused for pretraining, supervised fine-tuning, and RL post-training.</p>

<p><b>Architecture.</b> The backbone is Hy-Embodied-0.5-MoT, a 4B VLM with separate visual/text QKV and FFN parameters and shared attention for cross-modal interaction. The action expert is a second transformer tower (hidden size 1024, intermediate 2048, ~370M params) that shares attention with the VLM tower. The memory encoder wraps ViT blocks with factorized causal temporal-spatial attention and drops past-frame tokens before the VLM, so the token budget stays flat.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:hyvla:architecture]]</p>

<p><b>Action representation.</b> State and action are represented in the end-effector frame as 10-d vectors per arm: xyz translation, 6-d rotation, and gripper. The policy predicts delta chunks relative to the current end-effector pose, decoupling learning from robot kinematics. An optional “relabs” mode doubles the chunk with both relative and absolute targets and blends them at decode time.</p>

<p><b>What the code actually ships.</b> I cloned the repository and inspected it end to end. The architecture code is complete and runnable: MoT backbone fallback, dual-tower action expert, flow-matching head with Beta(1.5,1.0) timestep sampling and 10 Euler steps, KV-cache, parameter-free memory encoder, delta-chunk transforms, and training scripts for UMI pretraining and RoboTwin SFT. Public checkpoints and a ~2K-hour dataset are on Hugging Face.</p>

<p>However, two of the most emphasized system components are <b>not in the release</b>:</p>

<ul>
  <li><b>FlowPRO.</b> The offline RL post-training stage (Sec. 4) is marked “under review” in the README; a repo-wide grep for FlowPRO / RPRO / preference / intervention / rollback returns only README text and paper references, not implementation code.</li>
  <li><b>Async Bézier deployment.</b> The asynchronous inference framework with cubic-Bézier chunk stitching (Sec. 5.2–5.3) is not present. Only a synchronous RoboTwin policy wrapper is included.</li>
</ul>

