<hr/>

<h1>Cross-Cutting Observation — The Code-Release Gap</h1>

<p>Both deep-dive papers are framed as system contributions: μ₀ as a reusable cross-embodiment motion prior, HyVLA-0.5 as a full robot-learning stack. Both make real-robot claims. Yet both ship incomplete artifacts. μ₀ has no code at all as of this writing; HyVLA-0.5 ships the core model and training but omits FlowPRO and the async deployment stack that produce its most impressive real-robot numbers.</p>

<p>This pattern matters for two reasons. First, external signals — the thing that lets the field verify, extend, or falsify a paper — are weaker than the prose suggests. Second, the gap is structural: the parts most likely to contain hard-won engineering secrets (offline RL from human interventions, high-frequency closed-loop serving, long-horizon trace curation) are exactly the parts left out. Until they arrive, the prudent read is that both papers establish promising <i>directions</i> more than they establish reproducible <i>systems</i>.</p>

<h1>What This Run Learned</h1>

<ul>
  <li><b>3D traces are a plausible interface between video and control.</b> μ₀'s design — semantic keypoints, global 3D tracking, event-level captions, B-spline targets, frozen trace features for action experts — is coherent and the real-robot results are better than one would expect from video-only pretraining.</li>
  <li><b>The action-labeled path is not standing still.</b> HyVLA-0.5 shows that a MoT VLM, parameter-free temporal encoding, delta-chunk actions, and careful data engineering can push VLA performance without waiting for a video-only solution to mature.</li>
  <li><b>Released code is the binding constraint.</b> For both world-model approaches, the next research cycle depends on whether the missing pieces — TraceExtract and the action expert for μ₀, FlowPRO and deployment for HyVLA — are released and reproducible.</li>
</ul>

<p><b>Next questions worth following:</b> Can μ₀ scale beyond tabletop manipulation to mobile manipulators and dexterous hands? Does HyVLA-0.5's FlowPRO actually drive the claimed near-ceiling real-robot success when the code is released? And will the two philosophies converge — for example, by using μ₀-style trace pretraining to warm-start HyVLA-style action experts, reducing the need for 10K hours of action-labeled data?</p>
